explanation:
- OS_ObjectIdGetById: This function sets return_code used in the if-condition. Its implementation/return semantics are required to know whether the condition (return_code == OS_SUCCESS) can ever be true or is always false (which would make the subsequent block unreachable).
- OS_BinSemFlush_Impl: The body of the conditional assigns return_code from this function. Its prototype/implementation is needed to analyze whether the code inside the if-block contains reachable statements and what effects/returns it produces.
- OS_SUCCESS: The constant compared against return_code. Knowing its value/definition is needed to evaluate the branch condition and determine reachability.
- OS_LOCK_MODE_NONE: Passed into OS_ObjectIdGetById; the semantics of this mode may affect OS_ObjectIdGetById behavior and thus reachability of the if-block.
- LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE: Passed into OS_ObjectIdGetById; the object type can affect whether OS_ObjectIdGetById succeeds for given sem_id, so its definition/semantics are needed.
- osal_id_t: Type of sem_id parameter. Understanding its representation/valid ranges may be necessary to reason about call outcomes and whether particular inputs could make the branch reachable.
- OS_object_token_t: Type of token local variable passed to OS_ObjectIdGetById and OS_BinSemFlush_Impl. Its layout/usage could affect whether the calls succeed and so whether the code is reachable.
- int32: Definition/typedef of the return_code type. Needed to ensure comparisons and return semantics are well understood (signedness/width) when reasoning about reachable code.

These symbols together allow determining whether the if-condition can evaluate true for any valid input and therefore whether the block (and its inner call) is reachable; without them you cannot conclude compliance with the MISRA rule forbidding unreachable code.
